{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5290","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:49 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:49 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Of the various cases, it is the oblique that exhibits the greatest differences across the Literary and Spoken registers. It has more forms in Literary Tibetan, and the way in which it functions is more complex than in the spoken language. Traditionally referred to as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cmeaning of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span>,\u201d<a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]<\/a> the oblique actually subsumes three distinct markers: the markers <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> (and its variant <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>), <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> (and its variants <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f4f\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>), and finally <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>; a total of seven forms that are used as follows:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> is used after any ending (vowel or consonant)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> is used after any ending (vowel or consonant)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<a href=\"#_ftn2\"><\/a><\/span><a href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]<\/a> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> are used after vowels and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span> <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f4f\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span>, and after the <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">All these particles may function as the locative (without movement).<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Thus any word that ends in a consonant may be followed by one of three possible particles signifying the locative.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn Tibet\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f7a\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the mind\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f64\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f4f\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f64\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f64\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the (monastic) cell.\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">When a word ends in a vowel, there is the additional possibility of using the marker <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> instead of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span>:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn Lhasa\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f41\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f41\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f41\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> = <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f41\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cIn the sky\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p>However, each of the three markers has other specific functions that may be summarized briefly:<\/p><hr size=\"1\" \/><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]<\/a> There are three major problems with the way in which the <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> is traditionally presented in the Tibetan grammars. First, the three particles <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> are equivalent in the case of only one function (the locative without movement), but they differ in all other respects. Secondly, the grammatical analysis is based on the Sanskrit case models: accusative (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span>), dative (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span>), and locative (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>). The <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span> is subdivided into the possessive case (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f51\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span>), the case of object location (the locative proper) (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span>), the case of temporal location (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5a\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f90\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f47\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span>), and the case of object incorporation (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f49\u0f72\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f47\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span>). Finally, of the seven forms, some are actually variants of the same particle (for example <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f4f\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span>), whereas others correspond to quite different particles (for example <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span>). In my entries to the Reference Grammar, I do not adopt the traditional presentation, since it is too complex and is based on Sanskrit syntax, which is quite unrelated to that of Tibetan.<\/p><p>Mention may be made of one highly unusual feature of the oblique case in Literary Tibetan: it may follow other cases, notably the agentive and the ablative, in formulations such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"><em>\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f0b<\/em><\/span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"><em>\u0f53\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b<\/em><\/span>.<\/p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\">[2]<\/a> In the case of a \ufb01nal <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span>, the latter is replaced by the case marker <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>.<\/p>","title":""}]}
